<section type="titlepage">

<term lang="la">MANIPVLVS VOCABVLORVM.</term>
A Dictionarie of English
and Latine wordes, set forthe in
suche order, as none heretofore hath ben,
the Englishe going before the Latine,
necessary not onely for Scholers
that w<expan type="a+_">an</expan>t varietie of words,
but also for such as vse
to write in English
Meetre.

Gathered and set forth by P. Leuins.
<term lang="la">ANNO</term> 1570.

For the better vnderstanding of the order of this present
Dictionarie, read ouer the Preface to the Reader,
and the Epistle Dedicatorie, and thou shalt
finde it easie and plaine, and further
thereof thou shalt gather
great profite.

Imprinted at London by Henrie
Bynneman, for John Waley.
</section>

<section type="preface">

</page>

<page sig="para1v">

<heading>
THE PREFACE
to the Reader.
</heading>

sO many Dictionaries of Latin and English (gentle
Reader) haue now beene of late by diuers sundrye
writers set forth, that except some kind of Noueltie
should bring delite to the peruser, and some present
profite also giue hope and courage to the same, it
should be but a vaine thing, and counted but as lost
laboure, in so common a kind, and in so familiar a matter, to rea&#173;
sume againe, &#38; to begin a new, <expan type="y+e">the</expan> thing so often preu<expan type="e+_">en</expan>ted. Where&#173;
fore I thought it good &#38; expedient, at the beginning briefly to let
thee know and vnderstand what and how many commodities, be&#173;
sides other dictionaries, seeme to be contained in the compendious
compasse of this little booke, that thy hope may be certaine. Con&#173;
sidering therefore, that whereas he that writeth, meaneth euer to
pleasure some body, or to profit many: and yet so that he may sa&#173;
tisfy the best, and helpe them that haue most neede, and seeing that
the same thing then also commeth commonly to passe, when in the
least charges and paines, most profit &#38; pleasure redoundeth to the
perusers, therefore two things be here to be considered: first that
the quantitie is small, so that the price being little the poorer sorte
may be able to bie it: the other, that in the qualitie &#38; fourme of the
little quantitie, as it is deuised, be moe commodities, (than in the
common sort be founde) to be receiued: as for the quantitie, thou
seest what it is, certainely (as I call it) <term lang="la">Manipulum</term>, so it is but an
handfull: but as for the qualitie wherein the vertue is conteined,
mo peraduenture than thou wouldest easly thinke to be in so
little a booke that is hid from thee: what (sayest thou) &#38; how many?
surely these. First <expan type="y+t">that</expan> for the pleasantnesse of the metre, delectable &#38;
pleasant to reade (as it is in other tongs) both the wits be delited
and comforted, and the memorie also is nouryshed and confirmed,
so that a learned friend, being consulted concerning the edition
hereof, said that it would not onely helpe them that were willing
to learne, but also which is most necessarie in the negligent &#38; vn&#173;
willing youth, it would excitate &#38; stir them vp, so that they would
be willing to reade and to learne of them selues. Secondly wher&#173;

</page>

<page sig="para2r">

as it foloweth the alphabet of the order of the last sillible (for ther
is an alphabet well nigh as easie to be followed of the last sillable
as of the first) it commeth to passe, that when al the simple and vn&#173;
compo<expan type="u+_">un</expan>ded words be recited, and so many also of the compounds
and Deriuatiues as we thinke necessary and conuenient, all the
other, whether they be of Substantiues and Adiectiues out of
Verbes, or they be of Subst<expan type="a+_">an</expan>tiues &#38; Aduerbes out of Adiectiues,
or they be of Adiectiues out of Substantiues, or fynally of Sub&#173;
stantiues out of Substantiues, &#38; of Adiectiues out of Adiectiues,
and so forth of the rest, all the same I say by the rule of the Ter&#173;
mination, in whiche the Art of Deriuing and Compounding for
the most parte doth consist, wherein also the chiefe pointes of our
Grammer, where vnto the amplification &#38; variation of our tong
doth also properly belong, be here in many diuerse precepts, as
their places require, set forth &#38; considered. Thirdly, it is necessarie
for makers of meeter, so that it seemeth not only to redy him that
maketh, but also to giue him the way to learne the arte of the
same. Fourthly, wheras the chiefe grace and facilitie of our Eng&#173;
lishe tong, doth cheefly consist in long sillable and short, and in the
true pronouncing &#38; writing of the same, and namely in the end of
words, whervnto we haue most respect in this little worke, here&#173;
of it commeth to passe, that as wel children and ruder schoolers, as
also the Barbarous countries and ruder writers, may not a little
(if they wil enioy the offered occasion) well and easely correct and
amend, both their pen and speache. Fynally, wheras in the Polli&#173;
sillables, by diuersitie of pronunciation, and voyce of great accent,
oftentimes one worde maye haue diuers significations, as, differ,
d<emend err="i" source="errata">e</emend>fferre, <term lang="la">id est, prolongare</term>: and differ, <term lang="la">differre, id est, discrepare</term>, and
such other, we haue c<expan type="o+_">om</expan>monly set the accent, which is onely acute,
in that place, and ouer that vowell, where the sillable must go vp
&#38; be long. And so in conclusion, whatsoeuer belongeth to the three
cheefe poynts of Grammer, or Orthographie, Etimologie, &#38; Pro&#173;
sodie, there is little here omitted, that in suche a worke can be re&#173;
quired: wherfore if thou be minded to peruse this little booke, in
consideration of these commodities that we haue described: then
for thy better instruction in the order and vse of the same, peruse

</page>

<page sig="para2v">

first these articles and notes following, and so proceed to thy plea&#173;
sure and profit. Amen.
Notes for the vse of the booke.
First note that this Booke is deuided into ix. partes, according
to the ix. vowels, which come before the consonant in the last silla&#173;
ble: of the which vowels these fyue be simple, a.e.i o. and u. &#38; these
four, ay.ea.oy. &#38; ou. be Dipthonges: Note also that the Dipth<expan type="o+_">on</expan>ngs
be alwayes long, and that the other be alwayes short, except that
after a single C<emend err="o"><expan type="o+_">on</expan></emend>sonant, this letter, e. be the last letter of a word,
for then the letter (e) is not the vowel of the sillable, but it is only
added at the end, to make the sillable afore it to be long: as in these
abe. ebe. ibe obe. ube. (e) is only put to make the other vowels
long with (b) which else should be short if (e) were a way, as these
ab. eb. ib. ob. ub. &#38;c. whiche also be short, if it be a double consonant
though (e) do follow as. abbe. ebbe. ibbe. obbe. ubbe, and, ab. eb. ib
ob. and ub. be all one. Note thirdly, that first we set the short silla&#173;
bles and then the long, yet with this differ<expan type="e+_">en</expan>ce in both places, that
first all the monasillables be by th<expan type="e+_">em</expan>selues: yea &#38; in either of these
first all Substantiues by them selues, after warde all Verbes by
them selues, and finally all the adiectiues and other od parts of
speach, eche kind by them selues. Fourthly note, that whereas
some Terminations haue two or mo consonantes in the sillable
after the vowell, thou must follow the vowell, and the first conso&#173;
nant after it, as in these, au, auce, auche, aude, auge, augue. &#38;c.
followe the alphabet of A, Ante N. and thou shalt not misse him in
his place. Fiftly note, that when as some words here contained
be either barbarous, straunge, or fallen out of vse, we haue not <emend err="" source="errata">so</emend>
much put them in as imitable, but rather that the rude may re&#173;
forme their tong, and that the Readers of suche bookes, may here
learne what the wordes meane, and for that end we haue inter&#173;
preted such words, as kirke, church, myrke, darke, ken, know, and
such other. Sixtly, if any word be in diuers clause, the same is
witingly doone, in respect of diuerse kindes of writing, both which
are in vse, and like wise when one word hath diuers significations
we haue by adding some word to both in English and Latin, Di=

</page>

<page sig="para3r">

stincted and expounded the same: as the Gout in the hands <term lang="la">Chira&#173;
gra</term>, the Gout in the feete <term lang="la">Podagra</term>, a Pike for the eares teeth. &#38;c.
<term lang="la">scalprum</term>, a Pike pricke, <term lang="la">stimulus</term> a Pike fyshe, <term lang="la">Lupus fluuialis</term>.
Finally wheras the declenson, gender, or coniugation is some&#173;
times hard to know, we haue in the Nownes expressed the gene&#173;
tiue case, encreasing long with this circumflex (o) signifiing to be
declined with hec, except an other acticle be erpressed: and the
genetiue case encreasing short with this accent called graue (o)
signifying to be declined with <term lang="la">hic</term>, except an other article be ex&#173;
pressed: all other that haue neyther of these do not en&#173;
crease, and be declined with <term lang="la">hec</term>: except they end
in, er, or us, (for then they be <term lang="la">hic</term>) or in um,
and, e, (for then they be <term lang="la">hoc</term>) or haue
some other article expressed.

And to know the coniugations: we haue set ouer (e) the infi&#173;
nitiue moode of the seconde coniugations, this circum&#173;
fler (e) as <term lang="la">docere, <emend err="merere" source="errata">mereri</emend></term>, and ouer (e) the infini&#173;
tiue moode of the thirde, this accent graue (e)
as agere, fynally if any Verbe end not in
<term lang="la">ari</term>, eri, nor eri, but only in (i) as <term lang="la">frui</term>, it is
the infinitiue moode of the third
coniugation of some
Verbe in (or).

</page>

<page sig="para3v">

&#182; To the right worshipful M.Stanley
Treasurer of the Queene her Maiesties Mynt P.L.
wisheth helth, and all true felicitie.

IT is the manner of some writers (right worship&#173;
full) when they will set foorth some peece of worke,
that they haue compyled or made, to excuse the
rashenesse of the edition thereof, as beeing by their
friends counsell, or for some other cause, now mo&#173;
ued to comme<emend err="u">n</emend>d &#38; commit that to the vse or iudge&#173;
ment of many, which at first they thought should be but a priuat
excercise to them selues, or some priuie pleasure to a few. This
thing whether they all do in simplicitie of hart &#38; sinceritie, or some
of them for some other cause, I cannot iudge, but I do excase my
selfe that I do not follow the lowe steps of such humilitie, because
the truth is in deed, that at the beginning, when I first began to
collect this booke, which I haue now at last after a long time, and
with much more laboure and paines, than ye can possibly thinke,
c<expan type="o+_">on</expan>triued and brought to some perfection (for the gathering of oure
Englishe wordes, and deuiding of the same into this alphabet or&#173;
der of the last sillabls, being a trade not of any man afore attemp&#173;
ted, or by the other Dictionaries any thing to recken <emend err="vp" source="errata">vpon</emend> helped &#38;
furthered, must needs be a long trauaile) I thought and did alway
entend, with so much speed as I could, to publishe and set abroade
the same, as well for the commodities in the preface to the reader
contained, as also for conscience sake, thinking that wher I haue
bene long conuersant in the schooles, and haue from tyme to tyme
lamented to see the youth of our Cuntry (in the studie of the Latin
tong) lacke such little i<emend err="u">n</emend>struments, as this fit and needful for their
exercises, and sawe no man set his hand to the same, I was bound
for the portion of my small talent to do some what therin, though
I knowe that I shoulde for my laboure, ieoperd one of these two
displeasures: either if I did it not well, (for the world is now fine
and disdainefull) to be counted rude and ignorante, or else if I did
neuer so well (being harde to escape euill tongs) to be esteemed a

</page>

<page sig="para4r">

foole, as one that for suche a trifling thing as this, with lesse profyt
and more paines, would forsake a better and more worthie study,
with lesse trauaile and more gaynes. Yea and some will say more
ouer, that it is a superfluous &#38; vnnecessarie labour, to set forth this
Dictionarie, for so muche as Maister Howlet, hath sette forthe so
worthie a worke of the same kinde already. But I answere, that
though it be a worthy worke in deede, as it is most worthie, and
be also of the same kind in generall, <emend err="&#38;" source="errata"></emend> yet it is neyther of the same
kind in speciall, nor to the same purpose deuised in many things,
for his is great &#38; costly, this is little &#38; of light price, his is for gre&#173;
ter students, &#38; them <expan type="y+t">that</expan> are richable to haue it, this is for beginners,
&#38; them that are pooreable to haue no better, his is ful of phrases &#38;
sentences fit for them <expan type="y+t">that</expan> vse oration &#38; oratorie, this is onely stuf&#173;
fed full of words, &#38; the vse thereof fit for th<expan type="e+_">em</expan> that are not yet come
to better exercises, who if they should haue no Dictionarie at all
to help them forward, til such time as they were able to haue <emend err="one to vse," source="errata">or vse</emend> the other, <emend err="&#38;" source="errata">and</emend> ther be no more to be had but halfe ones that be
to no good purpose, what time should be lost? what years shoud be
spent? surely not alittle: like as if no man should worke in the
Mint, but such as brought with them golden hammers, ye should
haue little <emend err="workedone">worke done</emend>, whilst poore men, that for neede would la&#173;
bour, could not haue such tooles to worke withal, &#38; the rich which
peradu<expan type="e+_">en</expan>ture could haue them, yet for their accustomed ease &#38; idle
occupations, would take little paines therwith. Neither can they
wel say, <expan type="y+t">that</expan> though euery scholer may not priuatly, haue this great
Dictionarie, &#38; enioy her priuatly to him self: yet euery schoole hath
or may haue one of them in comm<expan type="o+_">on</expan>, which may serue for them al,
for neither will all parents so agree to haue one for all: and if they
would, yet it should be such a like thing, as if ye had but one toole
to worke with in the mynt, which whilst one workeman did occu&#173;
pie, al the other should be idle, and so the worke go little forward,
and surely by copie of Dictionaries, are copie of wordes coyned in
our schooles. But I neede not much c<emend err="e">o</emend>ntend in this matter being
playne inoughe of it selfe, nether do I so muche care for any of the
thinges aforesaide, either profit or paine, tauntes or disdaine, foo&#173;
lishnesse or finenesse, or for any of other such like vanities, as I do

</page>

<page sig="para4v">

(let th<expan type="e+_">em</expan> say what they wil) for my dutie towards the youth of my
Country, if perchance I might do them some pleasure herein: be&#173;
seching your Maistership in like manner, that youre worship will
for the same causes (for ye haue euer bene a louer &#38; helper of good
studies) neither be ashamed, nor displeased, to let so little and rude
a thing proceede in the commendation of youre good name to the
same end, seeing that here we seeke not for praise or profit, but for
the prosperous good proceeding of our poore youth in good learning
and knowledge, which thing if your goodnesse and pati<expan type="e+_">en</expan>ce wil do,
ye shall both bind and encourage me at all times, to my power
to laboure and endeuoure my selfe, <emend err="beth">both</emend> to further our
schooles with such poynts of my paines, and to gra&#173;
tifie your worship with a better work an other
day, and also ye shall deserue to be the best
benefactor in this businesse, and to be
partaker of all their prayers, that
may take profit hereby, to God
for your Mastership, in helth
and prosperitie, with en&#173;
crease of much worship
long to continue.
Amen.
</section>

<section type="errata">

</page>

these fautes escaped.

<section type="dictionary">

</xpln></wordentry>

</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="fistula(n)">
<expan type="y+e">the</expan> Fistula, disease </form> <xpln lang="la">Fistula, &#230;.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="sirrah(ex)">
Serrha, </form> <xpln lang="la">Heus, io.

<page sig="d2r">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="lave-eared(a)">
laue eared </form> <xpln lang="la">plaudus da
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="engrave(v)">
to ingraue </form> <xpln lang="la">insoulpere.
</xpln></wordentry>

Note that in these afore going in, auc,
the letter, w, cannot be put for v, ney&#173;
ther can the letter v, bee put for w, in
those that end, in awe: neither can the
one of them at any time be put for the
other so oft as a vowell foloweth th<expan type="e+_">em</expan>
bycause they both haue diuers signifi&#173;
cations, and also require contrary voice
in pronuntiati<expan type="o+_">on</expan>, as in these six folow&#173;
ing for example.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="saving(a)">
sauing of saue </form> <xpln lang="la">saluans, saluatio
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="roving(a)">
rouing of roue </form> <xpln lang="la">predatio
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="loving(a)">
louing of loue </form> <xpln lang="la">amans, amatio.
</xpln></wordentry>

But

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="sawing(a)">
sawing of saw </form> <xpln lang="la">seminatio
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="rowing(a)">
rowing of row </form> <xpln lang="la">remigatio
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="lowing(a)">
lowing of low </form> <xpln lang="la">boatio.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="daub(v)" lexeme="laud(v)" lexeme="stout(a)" lexeme="leud(a)">
But whensoeuer in the same word the
nexte letter folowing is a consonante,
then may ye indifferently wryte v, or
w, as daube or dawbe: laude, or lawde
stout, or stowt, leude or lewde, &#38;c. But
yet bycause this is the first place wee
describe all suche wordes by these that
end in au, hauing a consonant next let&#173;
ter as foloweth.</form> <xpln lang="la">
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="chaw(v)">
These folowing in, awe cannot for the
causes aforesayde in the note of aue, be
written in, aue, for in all these, w, hath
a vowel after it, by which vowel deri&#173;
uations be made, w, being stil vnchan&#173;
ged, as of chaw, chawed, chawing, cha&#173;
wer, &#38;c.</form> <xpln lang="la">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="untouched(a)">
vntouched </form> <xpln lang="la">intactus a
</xpln></wordentry>

There be also many other that ende in
ed, but namely of two sortes, the one
is of all pretertenses of verbes, both ac&#173;
tiue and passiue: as

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="loved(a)">
haue loued </form> <xpln lang="la">amaui, isti, it
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="read(a)">
had redde </form> <xpln lang="la">legeram as, at
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="blamed(a)">
bene blamed </form> <xpln lang="la">culpatus fui
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="tamed(a)">
was tamed </form> <xpln lang="la">domabar &#38;c.
</xpln></wordentry>

The other is of Participles of the pre<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
tertenses, which for the most part end
in ed, as

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="loved(a)">
loued </form> <xpln lang="la">amatus, dilectus
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="proved(a)">
prooued </form> <xpln lang="la">probatus a
</xpln></wordentry>

To these also may we adde certain per<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
ticiples, whiche being formed of Sub&#173;
stantiues, ende in ed, like participles, as,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="headed(a)">
headed of head </form> <xpln lang="la">capitatus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="eyed(a)">
eyed, of eye </form> <xpln lang="la">oculatus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="capped(a)">
capped of cappe </form> <xpln lang="la">piliatus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="coated(a)">
coted of cote. </form> <xpln lang="la">tunicatus
</xpln></wordentry>

The latine of these for the most parte
do ende in <term lang="la">atus</term>, as the exemples declare

1 There be also many other in en, of
three kynds, the first is of materials,
that is to say, of such woords as sig&#173;
nifie the substaunce wherof a thing
is made, as,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="linen(a)">
lynnen </form> <xpln lang="la">lineus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="leaden(a)">
leaden </form> <xpln lang="la">plumbeus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="woollen(a)">
woollen </form> <xpln lang="la">laneus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="leathern(a)">
leatherne </form> <xpln lang="la">pelliceus a
</xpln></wordentry>

&#38;c. The latine of these do ende in
<term lang="la">ens</term>, as the examples declare.

2 The seconde kynde is of preter&#173;
tenses of verbes, actiues, and passiues,
and of participles, as,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="beaten(a)">
haue beaten </form> <xpln lang="la">flagellaui
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="beaten(a)">
bin beaten </form> <xpln lang="la">flagellatus fui
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="beaten(a)">
beaten </form> <xpln lang="la">flagellatus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="eaten(a)">
eaten </form> <xpln lang="la">esus a. &#38;c.
</xpln></wordentry>

3 The thirde kind is of certayn plu&#173;
rall numbers of nounes, as treen for
trees, <term lang="la">arbores</term>. Stonen for stones, <term lang="la">lapi<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
des</term>, housen for houses, <term lang="la">&#230;des, i<expan type="u+_">un</expan></term>. &#38;c.

</wordgroup2>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="proper(a)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="familiar(a)">

</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="sinister(a)">

</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="improper(a)">

</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="unsure(a)">
vnsure </form> <xpln lang="la">incertus ta.
</xpln></wordentry>

Ther be many other in er, the which
we omit for breuines sake, namely
of three kyndes.

The first kynd is of the comparatiue
degree as harder, <term lang="la">durior</term>, of hard, <term lang="la">du&#173;
rus</term>: softer, <term lang="la">mollior</term>, of softe <term lang="la">mollis</term>:
whiter <term lang="la">albior</term>, of white <term lang="la">albus</term>: blac&#173;
ker, <term lang="la">nigrior</term>, of black <term lang="la">niger</term> &#38;c.
The second kynd is of noune subst<expan type="a+_">an</expan>&#173;
tiues verbals, aunswering to the la&#173;
tins in <term lang="la">tor</term> and <term lang="la">trix</term>: as of make <term lang="la">facio</term>,
maker <term lang="la">factor</term>: of bake <term lang="la">pinsere</term>, baker,
<term lang="la">pistor</term>: of heare, <term lang="la">audio</term>, hearer, <term lang="la">auditor</term>

</page>

<page sig="g3r">

of rede, <term lang="la">lego</term>, reder, <term lang="la">lector</term>, &#38;c.
The third kynd is of them that aun&#173;
swer to the latins, called gentiles: as 

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="londoner(n)">
of L<expan type="o+_">on</expan>don, L<expan type="o+_">on</expan>doner. </form> <xpln lang="la">Londinensis
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="inhabitant of louan(n)">
of Louan, Louaner, </form> <xpln lang="la">Louaniensis.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="inhabitant of bristol(n)">
of Bristow, bristoner, </form> <xpln lang="la">Bristoniensis.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="inhabitant of preston(n)">
of Preston, Prestoner, </form> <xpln lang="la">Prastonensis
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="britainer(n)">
of Britayn, Britaner, </form> <xpln lang="la">Britannus.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="inhabitant of rome(n)">
of Rome, Romaner, </form> <xpln lang="la">Romanus. &#38;c.
</xpln></wordentry>

Where note that this laste kynde is
both of countreis &#38; cities, and their
latine in <term lang="la">ensis</term>, and <term lang="la">anus</term>, as the exam&#173;
ples declare.

</wordgroup2>

<wordgroup1 type="a" object="es-">
<wordgroup2 type="a" object="ess">

Here folowe certaine words omitted before
of E <term lang="la">ante</term>  S, and E <term lang="la">ante</term>  T.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="harness(v)">
to harnesse </form> <xpln lang="la">armare
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="oppress(v)">
to oppresse </form> <xpln lang="la">opprimere
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="possess(v)">
to possesse </form> <xpln lang="la">possidire
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="profess(v)">
to professe </form> <xpln lang="la">profiteri
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="redress(v)">
to redresse </form> <xpln lang="la">reformare
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="repress(v)">
to represse </form> <xpln lang="la">reprimere
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="suppress(v)">
to suppresse </form> <xpln lang="la">supprimere
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="transgress(v)">
to transgresse </form> <xpln lang="la">transgredi
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="witness(v)">
to witnesse </form> <xpln lang="la">contestari
</xpln></wordentry>

There be also many other that end in
nesse, deriued of adiectiues, called of
gr<expan type="a+_">am</expan>matians substantiues denominati&#173;
ues, and must <emend err="besought">be sought</emend> in the place of
adiectiues in the order of metre if ye
will: as of bay, baynesse: of gay, gay&#173;
nesse: of glad gladnesse: of bad, bad&#173;
nesse &#38;c. Where it is to be noted, that
though many write this termination
in, nes, as goodnes, blacknes shortnes,
&#38;c. yet it is better to write them in
nesse, as goodnesse, blacknesse, shorte&#173;
nesse, &#38;c. Yea else some wold rede gre<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
dines, for gredinesse, law lines, for law<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
linesse, &#38;c. two sillables for three, the
latine of these end in <term lang="la">tas, tudo, cies, cia,
ies, <damage>ias:</damage> es</term>, is also a termination con&#173;
monly of the plurall number of sub&#173;
stantiues, &#38; be so many plural as there
be subst<expan type="a+_">an</expan>tiues singular, as stone, stones
bone, bones, way, wayes, day, dayes &#38;c.
There be moreouer many words that
ende in lesse, and be adiect<damage>i</damage>ues, signi&#173;
fying lacke of that which the substan&#173;
tiue signifieth, as in these that follow.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="beardless(a)">
beardlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">imberbis a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="careless(a)">
care<damage>l</damage>esse </form> <xpln lang="la">incurius a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="endless(a)">
endlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">infinitus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="harmless(a)">
harmelesse </form> <xpln lang="la">innocuus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="harbourless(a)">
harborlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">inhospitus a
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="lawless(a)">
lawlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">illex icis
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="merciless(a)">
mercylesse </form> <xpln lang="la">immisericors ordis
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="fatherless(a)">
fatherlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">orbus patre
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="motherless(a)">
motherlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">idem, orphanus a.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="painless(a)">
paynlesse </form> <xpln lang="la">indolens entis
</xpln></wordentry>

Est is also the terminacion of the se&#173;
cond persons singular of the present
tenses of all verbes actiues and neu&#173;
ters as.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="you(pr)" lexeme="love(v)">
thou louest </form> <xpln lang="la">ama<damage>s</damage></xpln></wordentry>

thou readest </form> <xpln lang="la">legis</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="you(pr)" lexeme="play(v)">
thou playest </form> <xpln lang="la">ludis</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="you(pr)" lexeme="pray(v)">
thou prayest </form> <xpln lang="la">oras, &#38;c.</xpln></wordentry>

This must be considered in metring
and in coniugating verbes of the a&#173;
ctiue and neuter signification.
Est is also the sign of the superlatiue
degree: as of fayre, fayrest, foule, fou&#173;
lest, &#38;c. For the L<damage>at</damage>ine looke thy
Grammer.

<page sig="h4v">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="yearly(n)">
yeerely </form> <xpln lang="la">annuatim, quot<expan type="a+_">an</expan>nis</xpln></wordentry>

Partly is also the signe of diminuti&#173;
ues as adiectiues: as,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="partly red(a)">
partly redde </form> <xpln lang="la">rubicundus a</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="partly fair(a)">
partly fayre </form> <xpln lang="la">pulchrellus a.</xpln></wordentry>

There be deriued of adiectiues, and
haue their latine in <term lang="la">ellus, ulus, uscu&#173;
lus.</term> &#38;c.

m&#230;tly, mediocriter, is vsed also
in the same sense that partly: as,
m<damage>ee</damage>tly fayre, pulchrellus. &#38;c.

There be also many other ending in
ly, perteyning to this place which we
omit for breuitie sake, but namely of
qualitie, as these that folowe, and such
other.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="gladly(adv)" lexeme="glad(n)">
gladly of glad </form> <xpln lang="la">l&#230;te, lubenter</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="madly(adv)" lexeme="mad(n)">
madly of mad </form> <xpln lang="la">stulte</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="barely(adv)" lexeme="bare(n)">
barely of bare </form> <xpln lang="la">nude, iter</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="rarely(adv)" lexeme="rare(n)">
rarely of rare </form> <xpln lang="la">raro</xpln></wordentry>

The english of all whiche is alwayes
thus fourmed by putting to, lye: and
the la<damage>ti</damage>n is formed of the adiectiue, by
turning us into e as <term lang="la">durus dure</term> or by
putting ter to the first case in i, as <term lang="la">duri,
dunter</term> &#38;c. neyther doth this rule on&#173;
ly holde in the positiue degree, but al&#173;
so in the comparatiue and superlatiue
degrees: As of <term lang="la">durior, durius,</term> hardlyer
or more hardly, of <term lang="la">durissimus, duris&#173;
sime</term>, hardliest, or most hardly. &#38;c.
<note>
Antedates earliest occurrence of "hardliest" in OED "hardly, adv." (6; 1597). 
"Hardlier" is not noted there.
</note>

</wordgroup2>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="involuntary(a)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="voluntary(a)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="watery(a)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="weary(n)">
wearie </form> <xpln lang="la">fessus a</xpln></wordentry>

There be also diuerse other that ende
in rye here omitted for breuities sake,
which may be called a kinde of deno&#173;
minatiues, but muche differing from
the nature of them in tie or, in nesse,
for two causes: first that wher as those
are d<damage>e</damage>riued of adiectiues, and formed
of the same, as, of <term lang="la">grauis</term>, e, heauie, are
formed heauinesse or grauitie: and of
<term lang="la">bonus, a,</term> good, are formed goodnesse,
or bountie, for bountie is written for
bonity: these contrarie in rye are for&#173;
med of substantiues: as of armour ar&#173;
morie, of draper draperie of slaue sla&#173;
uerie, and such other: secondly bycause
that where as the other do signifie for
the moste parte some qualitie, as the
foresayd examples declare, <emend err="" source="errata">these contrary</emend> signifie ey&#173;
ther some place as of harbour harbou<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
rie, <term lang="la">hospitium</term>, of coney conyrie, <term lang="la">lepo&#173;
rarium</term>: or else some office as of baud,
baudrye, <term lang="la">lenocinium</term>, of begger beg&#173;
ger beggerie <term lang="la">mendicitas</term>, or else some
instrument, as of dyet dyetarie, <term lang="la">dieta&#173;
rium</term>: of briefe <term lang="la">breuiare, breuiatium</term>
&#38;c. fynally though these be the chiefe
naturs of oure english woords in rie,
yet haue we not excluded certeine o&#173;
ther which come of adiectiues and of
verbs, as of braue, brauerie, splendor,
of flatter flatterye, <term lang="la">adulatio</term>. But by&#173;
cause these be so few that they require
no rule, we leue them to be obserued,
noting this finally, that the other in
rie, which come of substantiues, haue
their latine commonly in <term lang="la">arium</term>, as
the examples declare.
<note>
Antedates earliest OED citation for "bonity" (1585).
</note>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="guilty(a)">
giltie </form> <xpln lang="la">reus a, conscius a</xpln></wordentry>

There bee also many other in tye,
here for breuite sake omitted, which
thou mayst form wh<expan type="e+_">en</expan> thou wilt, of
this termination, tas, being one kynd
of denominatiues, whose english al&#173;
so endeth in nesse, of which we haue
sayd in this place before: neyther do
they differ any thing in sense or sig&#173;
nification, but only in the end or ter&#173;
minacion as these that folow.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="felicity(n)" lexeme="happiness(n)">
felicitie, or happynesse </form> <xpln lang="la">f&#230;lscitas</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="dignity(n)" lexeme="worthiness(n)">
dignitie, or worthyuesse </form> <xpln lang="la">dignitas

<term lang="en">For dignitie and worthynesse be all
one: and felicitie and happynesse be
all one: and so forth in others. Final&#173;
ly in this they only differ, that those
in tye are formed of the latyn word,
and the other in nesse, are formed of
the englishe woord.</term></xpln></wordentry>

</wordgroup2>
<wordgroup2 type="a" object="vie or -vye">In vie, or vye.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="envy(n)">
enuie </form> <xpln lang="la">inuidia &#230;</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="navy(n)">
A nauy </form> <xpln lang="la">nauigium i</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="replevy(n)">
a repleuie </form> <xpln lang="la">repignoratio</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="obloquy(n)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="envy(v)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="replevy(v)">
to repleuie </form> <xpln lang="la">repignorare</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="heavy(a)">
heauie </form> <xpln lang="la">grauis e</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="privy(a)">
priuie </form> <xpln lang="la">secretus a</xpln></wordentry>

There be also many other that ende
in ie, or ye, formed of substantiues,
and they be adiectiues signifying
plenty of that thing, which the sub&#173;
stantiues betoken, and they aunswer
to the adiectiues in <term lang="la">osus</term>, and in <term lang="la">en&#173;
tus</term>, as these that folow. 

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="stone(n)">
of stone </form> <xpln lang="la">lapis</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="stony(a)">
stony </form> <xpln lang="la">lapidosus a</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="bone(n)">
of bone </form> <xpln lang="la">es </xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="bony(a)">
bony cometh </form> <xpln lang="la">ossosus a</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="blood(n)">
of bloud </form> <xpln lang="la">cruor </xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="bloody(a)">
bloudy </form> <xpln lang="la">cruentus a</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="flood(n)">
of floud </form> <xpln lang="la">fluctus </xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="floody(a)">
floudy </form> <xpln lang="la"> fluctuosus, a</xpln></wordentry>

and they be expounded by the word
full, as <term lang="la">faxosus, a,</term> stony, or full of
stones, <term lang="la">sanguinulentus, a,</term> bloudy or
full of bloud, &#38;c. These be common
to all terminacions in ie, or in ye.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="twibill(n)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="credible(a)">
credible </form> <xpln lang="la">credibilis le</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="incredible(a)">
incredible </form> <xpln lang="la">incredibilis le</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="divisible(a)">
diuisible </form> <xpln lang="la">diuisibilis le</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="indivisible(a)">
indiuisible </form> <xpln lang="la">indiuisibilis le</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="sensible(a)">
sensible </form> <xpln lang="la">sensibilis le</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="insensible(a)">
insensible </form> <xpln lang="la">insensibilis e</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="vendible(a)">
vendible </form> <xpln lang="la">vendibilis le</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="terrible(a)">
terrible </form> <xpln lang="la">terribilis le</xpln></wordentry>

There are also many of this kynd be&#173;
side these, which are of the same signi<emend err="">&#173;</emend>
fication, that those which end in able,
but they differ in forming. For those
in able, are formed of the english the&#173;
me: as speakable, <term lang="la">effabilis</term>, eatable, <term lang="la">co&#173;
mestilis, le</term>, treatable, <term lang="la">tractabilis le</term>: of
speake, eate and treate: but these in ible
are formed of the latin theme: as legi&#173;
ble, <term lang="la">legibilis, e</term>: audible, <term lang="la">audibilis le</term>, s<expan type="e+_">en</expan>&#173;
sible, <term lang="la">sensibilis le</term>: of <term lang="la">lego, audio, sen&#173;
tio.</term> &#38;c. Yet in this they agree, that
both of them are deriued of verbs: and
that they haue both one verbe answe&#173;
ring to their signification in latin: for
both readable, and legible, signifie <term lang="la">le&#173;
gibilis le</term>, deriued of <term lang="la">Lego</term>. And feele&#173;
able and sensible, signifie <term lang="la">sensibilis</term> of
<term lang="la">Sentio</term>. &#38;c.
</wordgroup2>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="utensil(a)">
vtensile </form> <xpln lang="la">vtensilis le</xpln></wordentry>

Note, that ofttimes ble, is written for
bil, dle, for dil, fle, for fil, gle, for gil,
kle, for kil ple, for pil, sle, for fil, tle,
for til, ule, for uil. And these for the
other agayne indifferently as

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="amble(n)">
amble, or ambil. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="saddle(n)">
sadle, or sadil. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="stifle(n)">
sti<damage>f</damage>le, or stifil </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="pigil(n)">
pigil, for pigil: </form> <xpln lang="la">verbasculum</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="gargle(n)">
gargle, or gargil </form> <xpln lang="la">
</xpln>
<lemenote>
Antedates earliest OED citation (1657).
</lemenote>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="mussel(n)">
muskle, or muskil. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="staple(n)">
staple, or stapil </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="hassle(n)">
hastle, or hastil. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="hazel(n)">
hasle, or hasil. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="title(n)">
title, or titil. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="tavell(n)">
taule, or tauil, &#38;c. </form> <xpln lang="la"></xpln></wordentry>

Wherfore, if ye fynd not in the one
of these seeke in the other and yee
shal not misse.

More ouer, this termination bil, an&#173;
swereth in englishe, commonly to
the adiectiues in bilis, as we haue
sayd in the terminations able, and
ible, for which, the termination bil
is putte, looke in the other

</wordgroup2>

<wordgroup2 type="a" object="ilde">In ilde.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="child(n)">
A chyld </form> <xpln lang="la">puer, eri, hic</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="field(n)">
A field </form> <xpln lang="la">ager i, hic</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="mild(a)">
mylde </form> <xpln lang="la">blandus da</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="wild(a)">
wylde </form> <xpln lang="la">ferus ra</xpln></wordentry>

This terminacion, ilde, is oftymes in
metre put for participles in <emend err="ilde" source="errata">iled</emend>, as,
fylde, for filed, tyld, for tyled, but I
think, that they should be written in`
yeld: as defield, for defiled: begielde
for begyled, &#38;c.

</wordgroup2>
<wordgroup2 type="a" object="ilte">In ilte.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="hilt of a sword(n)">
<expan type="y+e">the</expan> hilt of a sworde. </form> <xpln lang="la">manubrium ij</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="quilt(n)">
A quilt </form> <xpln lang="la">culcitra &#230;</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="stilt(n)">
A stilt </form> <xpln lang="la">grallus li</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="built(a)">
bilt </form> <xpln lang="la">&#230;dificatus a</xpln></wordentry>

This termination, ilte, is also often
written for participles in, illed, with
double, ll, as fillde, for filled: spilt for
spilled: kylte, for killed, and such o&#173;
ther.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="filth(n)" lexeme="drab(n)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="belonging(adv)">
Belonging: </form> <xpln lang="la">pertinens, spectans:</xpln></wordentry>

Belonging, is also the signe of adie&#173;
ctiues <emend err="passiues" source="errata">possessiues</emend>, as, belonging the gar&#173;
den, <term lang="la">hortensis</term>, belonging the field, <term lang="la">a&#173;
grestis</term>. The lyke is to be thought of
this woorde perteynyng, <term lang="la">pertinens,
spectans</term>, as perteyning to my father,
<term lang="la">paternus</term>, a, perteyning my mother,
<term lang="la">maternus</term>. &#38;c.
There be also certaine nounes ending
in ling, here to be formed, when ye
will, as.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="gosling(n)" lexeme="goose(n)">
Gosling of goose, </form> <xpln lang="la">anserculus i</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="duckling(n)" lexeme="duck(n)">
duckling of ducke, </form> <xpln lang="la">anaticulus i</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="porkling(n)" lexeme="pork(n)">
porkling of porke, </form> <xpln lang="la">porcellus i</xpln></wordentry>

These be diminitiues, &#38; may be ex&#173;
pounded by this signe little, as gos&#173;
ling, or little goose, porkling or lit&#173;
tle porke And their Latin endeth for
the most parte in, <term lang="la">ulus</term>, or in <term lang="la">ellus</term>, as,
<term lang="la">anserculus porcellus</term> &#38;c.
There be also many other that end in
ing, here not expressed, because they
may be deriued out of verbes three
maner of wayes when ye will, after
this sort, first participles of the pre&#173;
sent tenses, as louing, teaching, rea&#173;
ding, of loue, teach, rede by put<damage>ti</damage>ng to
(ing) whose Latine is easely formed
of the gerund in, <term lang="la">di</term>, by turning <term lang="la">di</term> in&#173;
to, <term lang="la">s</term>, as, <term lang="la">amandi, amans, docendi, do&#173;
cens, legendi, legens</term>. &#38;c.
2 The second kinde is of the ge&#173;
rundes of verbs, as <term lang="la">amandi</term> of louing,
<term lang="la">docendi</term> of teching, <term lang="la">leg<expan type="e+_">en</expan>di</term> of reding.
3 The third kind is of nounes ver&#173;
bals, whose Latine ending in, <term lang="la">io</term>, or <term lang="la">us</term>
is formed of the latter supine, as, <term lang="la">lo&#173;
uing amatio, onis, h&#230;c</term>, of <term lang="la">amatu</term>, rea&#173;
ding, <term lang="la">lectio, onis, h&#230;c</term>, of <term lang="la">lectu</term>, hea&#173;
ring <term lang="la">auditio, onis, h&#230;c, auditus, vs</term>, do&#173;
ing <term lang="la">actio, onis, h&#230;c, actus, us, hic.</term> Of al
these kindes the englishe is one, but
the Latine is diuers, as the examples
declare

</wordgroup2>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="overskip(v)">
to ouerskip </form> <xpln lang="la">pr&#230;terire, omittere</xpln></wordentry>

There be also many other, that ende
in, shippe, signifying artes or offices,
and be deriued of substantiues, as are
these folowing,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="majorship(n)" lexeme="major(n)">
maiorship of maior, </form> <xpln lang="la">maioratus us
</xpln>
<lemenote>
The noun "majorship" antedates its earliest OED citation (1717).
</lemenote>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="bailieship(n)" lexeme="bailie(n)">
bay<emend err="i">l</emend>yship of bayly, </form> <xpln lang="la"><emend err="villicus" source="errata">villicatus</emend> us</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="bishopship(n)" lexeme="bishop(n)">
byshopship of byshop, </form> <xpln lang="la">episcopatus us</xpln></wordentry>

The latine of these for the most part
endeth either in atus, us, of the fourth
decl<expan type="e+_">en</expan>son, as the examples declare: or
else in ura, e, of the first decl<expan type="e+_">en</expan>son, as
prelatura, &#230;, pr&#230;tura e, qu&#230; stura, &#38;c.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="limpish(a)">
lympish </form> <xpln lang="la">claudus a</xpln></wordentry>

There be many in ishe besyde these,
namely of two sorts: the one deriued
of subst<expan type="a+_">an</expan>tiues, the other of adiectiues,
and bothe be adiectiues diminutiues,
signifying some affection, inclination
or degree of the primitiue: as of wa&#173;
ter, aqua, cometh waterish, or some&#173;
what watry, aqueus, aquaticus, a: of red
rubeus, a, someth reddish, rubicundus,
da. &#38;c. These bee also put often for
those in ie, whose latine end in, osus,
and entus, as aforsayde,, as slepyshe or
full of slepe, sleepy, somnulentus, ta. &#38;c.
The Latine of these ende in eus, ellus,
or ulus.

</wordgroup2>
<wordgroup2 type="a" object="isme">In isme.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="schism(n)">
A scisme </form> <xpln lang="la">scnismus, mi</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="baptism(n)">
baptisme </form> <xpln lang="la">baptismus</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="sophism(n)">
A sophisme </form> <xpln lang="la">sophisma atis, hoc</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="exorcism(n)">
an exorcisme </form> <xpln lang="la">exorcismus mi</xpln></wordentry>

There be diuers other, that do end in
isma, are derined of latine woords and
greeke wordes, in isma, and inising,
and they be of three fortes.

</page>

<page sig="m3r">

The first is of <emend err="c">t</emend>he common speche,
as these aforesayd: The second be ta&#173;
ken of a countrey or language, as of
latine latinisma, latinismus, i, Grecke,
Gr&#230;cisme, Gr&#230;cismus, i, H&#230;brew, He&#173;
braisme, h&#230;braismus, i, Barbarie, bar&#173;
barisme, barbarismus, i, laconic, laco&#173;
nisme, lacomsmus, i, atticke, atticisme
Atticismus, i, Britannie, Britanisme,
Bri<emend err="c">t</emend><expan type="a+_">an</expan>ismus, i. Scotte, Scotisme, scotis&#173;
mus, i, and many other. The third, is
of sectes and factions, wh<expan type="o+_">om</expan> we cal af&#173;
ter the masters and beginners of o&#173;
pinions and doctrines, as of pape, pa&#173;
pisme, papismus, i, Luther, Lucherams&#173;
me, Lutheranismus, Ariane, Arianis&#173;
me, Aranismus, i, Caluine, Caluynis&#173;
me, Caluinismus, i. Plato, Platonisme,
Platonismus, and such other sects, the
folowers wherof do end in ist, as, Bap
tiste, baptista, &#230;, hic, sophiste, sophista, e
latioiste, latinista. e, laconiste, laconista
papiste, papista, &#230;, Platoniste, Platoni&#173;
sta, &#230;, and such other, as many or mo
as ende in isme<emend err="" source="errata">, and are deryued of latine and greek wordes
in <term lang="la">isma</term> and in <term lang="la">ismus</term></emend>: for commonly they
haue bothe one primitiue: the first,
signifying the sect it selfe, tongue, or
manner of people, and the latter bee&#173;
tokening him, that eyther is good &#38;
canning, or else is studious and ear&#173;
nest in the same.

</wordgroup2>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="proclive(a)">
procliue </form> <xpln lang="la">procliuis ue</xpln></wordentry>

There be many other in iue, deriued
out of verbes, whereof some <emend err="f">s</emend>ignifie
actiuely, as affections whiche moue,
and othersome passiuely, as affected
with some thing: the next folowing
be actiues and such other.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="defensive(a)">

These folowing, and such other, doo
rather signifie passiuely: as

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="incostive(a)">

Finally these in iue, can not be wri&#173;

the termination aue, if thou doubt,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="of(pp)">
of </form> <xpln lang="la">a, ab, de.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="thereof(adv)">
therof </form> <xpln lang="la">inde</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="whereof(adv)">
wherof </form> <xpln lang="la">vnde</xpln></wordentry>

Of, is also the signe of the genitiue
case, as of me, <term lang="la">mei</term>, of thee, <term lang="la">tui</term>. &#38;c. al&#173;
so the signe of an ablatiue, or datiue
after passiues: as I am taught of thee,
<term lang="la">Doccor a te</term>: seene of me, <term lang="la">visus mihi</term>,
also the signe of adiectiues, possessi&#173;
ues, and materialls: as <term lang="la">paternus</term>, a of
my father <term lang="la">maternus</term> a, of my mother:
<term lang="la">aureus</term>, a of gold, <term lang="la">arg<expan type="e+_">en</expan>teus</term>, a, of siluer.
Finally, it is the signe of a datiue case,
after adiectiues in <term lang="la">bilis</term>, and partici&#173;
pials in <term lang="la">dus</term>, as <term lang="la">visibilis omnibus</term>, able
to be seene of all men, <term lang="la">amandus om&#173;
nibus</term> to be loued of all men.

forined of substantiues, as

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="millocke(n)">
millocke, </form> <xpln lang="la">parua mola</xpln></wordentry>

and other, whose Latin is in vlus, vla,
ellus, ella, as the examples declare, &#38;
must be expounded be this signe, lit&#173;
tle,or small, as, hillocke, or litle hil,
pillock, or small pill, &#38;c.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="union(n)">
an vnion </form> <xpln lang="la">vnio onis, h&#230;c</xpln></wordentry>

There bee also many other beside
these which end in on, and are to bee
deriued, when ye wil of the later su&#173;
pine of the Latine verbe, by turning
v, into, iou, like as the Latine nounes
(for they be nounes verbals) are for&#173;
med of the same, by turning, u, into
io, as in these that folowe and suche
other.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="relation(n)">
relation </form> <xpln lang="la">relatio</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="revelation(n)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="revolution(n)">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="vocation(n)">
a vocation </form> <xpln lang="la">vocatio</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="visitation(n)">
a visitation </form> <xpln lang="la">visitatio</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="unction(n)">
vnction </form> <xpln lang="la">vnctio. &#38;c.</xpln></wordentry>

All which make the genetiue case in
onis, and are declined with h&#230;c, there
be almost as many of them as there
be Latine verbes of the actiue signi&#173;
fication to be found.

</wordgroup2>

<wordgroup2 type="a" object="opt">In opt.

This termination opt, is written for
opped, in the participles of the preter
tense: as stopt, for stopped, lopt, for
lopped, propt, for propped, &#38;c.

Se<emend err="c">e</emend>ke other in, ou, hauing conso&#173;
na<emend err="o">n</emend>tes after them in theyr places, as,
ou, <term lang="la">ante</term> , b, ou, <term lang="la">ante</term> , c, ou, <term lang="la">ante</term> , d. &#38;c.
for, ou is a letter compounded, that is
a Diphthonge vowell, and hathe his
place in the Alphabete order afore
the consonantes, and is the last of the
same, in this booke,

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="unwoeful(a)">
vnwoful </form> <xpln lang="la">indolens</xpln></wordentry>

There bee also many other which
end in full, heere omitted, whose La&#173;
tine doth end in (<term lang="la">osus) entus</term>, <term lang="la">lis</term> or in
(<term lang="la">dus</term>) these ye may forme out of sub&#173;
stantiues, as we also sayde of them,
that ende in (ic) when ye will: and
they signifie plentie, or much of that
which the substantiue betokeneth, as

In osus.

Great is also the signe of certayne ad&#173;
iectiues, deriued of verbes called ver&#173;
bals in ax: as

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="great eater(n)">
great eater </form> <xpln lang="la">edax acis</xpln></wordentry>

It is also the signe of diuers other ad&#173;
iectiues that answer to them in osur,
when this signe full can not be vsed,
as ventrosus, we cal great bellyed, bi&#173;
cause we can not wel say, full of bel&#173;
lyes. &#38;c.

in foulde, do signifie the place where

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="inferior(n)">
inferioure </form> <xpln lang="la">inferior oris</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" lexeme="soldier(n)" lexeme="piller(n)" lexeme="slander(n)" lexeme="danger(n)" lexeme="printer(n)" lexeme="teacher(n)" lexeme="reader(n)" lexeme="doctor(n)" lexeme="proctor(n)" lexeme="senior(n)" lexeme="junior(n)">
Some write oure, for er, as sodioure,
for sodier, pilloure for piller, sclan&#173;
doure, for sclander, dangeoure for
danger, printoure for printer, tea&#173;
choure for teacher, redoure for reder &#38;c.
Some also oure, for or, as doctoure for
doctor, proctoure for proctor, seni&#173;
oure for senior, iuniour, for iunior &#38;c.
</form> <xpln lang="la">Wherfore if any be here not expressed,
seeke them in one of the other, and
thou shalt finde it, or some rule how
to knowe it and to deriue it, if it bee
such lyke.</xpln></wordentry>

All which be of the same significati&#173;
on that some of those deriuatiues are
of, which end in, ie, as we sayde in his
place, and seeme for the moste part to

furiouse of furiosus, famouse of fa&#173;
